title: Acrylic Laser Cut Direct Drive Extruder

description.text: A direct drive extruder which can be cut in acrylic.

Updated Design on 10 April I built this extruder, and found that there was no space for me to mount a pneumatic push fit connector, and hence, I have replicated the bottom of the extruder. Based on the size of the drive gear/hobbed gear, you can cut as many pieces of the bottom horizontal bar in the design, and while assembling stack them and stick them with CA glue or epoxy. Measure the center of the filament and then drill, tap to have space for the bottom of the Push Fit connector to be fixed. I used a 4mm to M5 Push fit connector which grips the 4 mm PTFE tube snuggly, which acts as the bowden tube. The hole for the M5 screw which fits for the bearing also has been reduced in diameter for 5 mm to 3.9 in design, to ensure there is sufficient acrylic to tap an M5 thread in the hole. Other changes include increasing the size of the spring notches to ensure the part is strong under the stress of the spring and doesnt break off.

I Designed the entire extruder parts in Openscad, then projection on z=0 plane yielded the dxf.  
Use atleast 8mm thick acrylic to ensure stiffness. The bearing used is 625ZZ, but the design can be edited to accommodate a smaller bearing.  This bearing is most commonly available in window rollers and can be purchased from hardware stores.  
Mounting directly on the motor is not recommended, because the 2mm flange of the shaft will interfere with this extruder.  
Use a spring to maintain even tension on the filament between the notches provided on the arm and the mount( see dxf to understand how this is done.)

comments.text:
RushMoreMods- The extruder has been made so that the filament can be guided using a bowden tube.
I do not think that the acrylic will melt if the design is such that the extruder sits on top of the hot end, because there has to be sufficient cooling in the hot end to ensure that the filament does not melt midway on its path to the nozzle. This is the major reason for clogged hot ends.

title: Canister-type Hepa Filter Adapter (Universal)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
This is an adapter for a ~215mm canister-type air filter(measured end-to-end, external dimension). You can use a number of standard types of filters, but since this is for a clean room project, I chose extremely high partial filtration parameters.

The unit is designed for use with a particular format of filter, with a deep tongue-in-groove seating. This seal is entirely dependent on the pressure generated from preloading the vulcanized end towards the open end of the canister, accomplished by an oversized, semi-spherical plug on the leading end of the device. On the exit side of the filter adapter, there is a plain, unflanged, circular 60mm opening. This is intended for a specific adapter I plan on using, but other modes of attachment can easily be designed and printed, ad hoc. I may add additional adapters to be printed separately, hand fitted, and adhered with Methyl Ethyl Ketone based glue (medium bodied, for polymers, of course). This has been marked [WIP] since I may upload more adapters for this as a sub-assembly.

A fine screen will be fitted on the egress piping of the completed assembly. It's important that this device is sealed, either thermally or with a polymer safe enamel that will not chip, in order to minimize the risk of both unfiltered air leaks and debris from printing artifacts.

Use this device at your own risk, use common sense in your application. Do not use ABS plastic, this was designed to be printed with rigid PLA, high infill density, and tight tolerances. Do not use this in an environment with ambient temperatures in excess of 85 degrees F to avoid material out-gassing or deformation as this part will be under load with a filter installed, or in the presence of any type of solvent vapors, organic or otherwise. It may be wise to employ a secondary coarse foam/mesh filter to avoid ingress of debris of printer artifacts or any other debris in case of a failure. If you're not sure about these things, maybe you shouldn't be doing whatever you are doing.

Enjoy.

Modular Grip system for GPD-Win gaming device.

Update: GRIP MODS published for this Dock:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2719431

This project is my own vision about how to implement a modular grip to GPD-Win. I decided to implement a base docking that you must "plug" on the GPD-Win, and extend it using modules, as examples, Grips, for get better and comfortable usage of the device.

The concept really is simple. For the first version i released a grip based on 5 pieces:

  • Base with docking system for modules. This base come with a bottom surface that help to user to avoid burning their fingers by the heating of the device, when playing.
  • Left Grip, divided on two parts for mounting on the Docking.
  • Right Grip, divided on two parts for mounting on the Docking.

Features:

Dock version 2 (Happy Face)

  • Revised System for dock the GPD-Win. Now simply put the GPD-Win, and using the screw holes, you simply "plug" the device on the docking
  • Revised rail system for docking modules, adjusting size for smooth glide.
  • Revised fixation system, for get the module stable and fixed to the Dock.
  • Added mic slot on the Dock.
  • Added slots for better ventilation of the bottom of the device.
  • Added a bigger slot for use a wirst strap (front ventilation holes)
  • Added slot for fan switch
  • Added Space Invaders logo on front

Grips Version 1

  • Right GRIP: Redirected audio output to bottom. This allow to put the device on a flat surface like a table, and make the sound to expand on their surface.
  • Left GRIP: Redirected ventilation flow in to bottom. This avoid to obstruct these slots with hands.
  • Added small horns on the bottom. This is for better usage of the device, helping to avoid falls or grab the device using this part.
  • Added a form factor to allow to put (and rest) forefingers on it, without accidentally pressing L1/R1
  • Grips have comfortable form factor, that allow to easily grab the device, and help when are on a surface to get better air flow under the device.

I'm using a Ender 2 printer, that have a printable surface of 150x150x200mm. For this reason i decided to adopt the modularized concept of this Grip, for allow to be printed on small priners like this.

Now, i'm working on alternative grips that will be released to complement this project.

my list to do, and future releases are the following:

  • Audio mod: drive the sound output for top of the grip.
  • Box Mod: Add a box on the bottom of the dock, for installing some HDD, Power Bank, etc.

Fell free on comment and post your suggestions for implement on future grips.

Thanks to guys from Telegram groups, for their feedback and suggestions!

ESPAÑOL
Sistema modular de Grips para la consola GPD-Win

ACTUALIZACIÓN: PUBLICADOS GRIPS ALTERNATIVOS:
https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2719431

Este proyecto es mi propia visión de cómo implementar un sistema modular de grips para la GPD-Win. He decidido implementar una base "Estación" (desde ahora la llamaré Dock) que debes instalar en la GPD-Win, y extender esta base utilizando módulos, como por ejemplo grips para ganar en comodidad a la hora de utilizar la consola.

El concepto realmente es muy simple. Para la primera versión he publicado un grip compuesto en 5 piezas

  • Docking base para el sistema de módulos. Esta base viene con una superficie inferior que ayuda a prevenir que el usuario toque directamente la consola, evitando el calor que esta produce en ocasiones y que puede resultar molesto.
  • Grip izquierdo, dividido en 2 partes para montar en el Docking
  • Grip derecho, dividido en 2 partes para montar en el Docking

Note: apologize my poor and rude english.

Características:

Dock versión 2 (Happy Face)

  • Sistema para montar la GPD-Win revisado. Ahora simplemente pon la GPG-Win en el dock y utilizando los agujeros de los tornillos, simplemente "encaja" el dispositivo en el docking. Quedará fijo sin necesidad de mecanismos extra.
  • Sistema de rieles para instalar módulos revisado. Se ha ajustado el tamaño para permitir un deslizamiento suave.
  • Sistema de fijación revisado. Ahora los módulos quedan estables instalados en el Dock.
  • Agregado agujero para el micrófono en el Dock.
  • Agregadas ranuras en superficie inferior del Dock, para mejorar la ventilación del dispositivo.
  • Agregadas ranuras para mejorar la ventilaciónd el dispositivo (ranuras frontales)
  • Se ha agrandado la ranura para instalar una pulsera de seguridad (anclada en la parte frontal de la consola, en los agujeros de ventilación)
  • Agregada ranura para permitir cambiar el switch del ventilador.
  • Agregado logo de Space Invaders en el frente

Grips Versión 1

  • GRIP Derecho: Se ha redireccionado la salida del audio a la parte inferior. Esto permite que cuando tengamos el dispositivo en una superficie plana como una mesa, el audio se expanda por la superficie.
  • GRIP Izquierdo: Se ha redireccionado la entrada de aire desde abajo. Esto ayuda a evitar que estas ranuras (en la consola) se vean obstruídas por las manos del usuario cuando utiliza el dispositivo.
  • Se han agregado pequeños cuernos en la parte inferior de los grips. Esto ayuda a mejorar el agarre del dispositivo.
  • El diseño de la parte superior del grip (parte trasera) permite que podamos poner el dedo índide en el grip para descansar o agarrar la consola, sin que presionemos accidentalmente los botones L1 y R1
  • Los grips tienen una forma cómoda, que permite un mejor agarre del dispositivo, y que cuando lo ponemos en una superficie, ayuda a tener mas ventilación en la parte inferior de la consola.

Actualmente estoy utilizando una impresora Ender 2, la cual tiene una superficie de impresión de 150x150x200. Por este motivo he decidido adopoptar un concepto modular del Grip, para que sea posible de imprimir en impresoras compactas como esta.

Actualmente estoy trabajando en grips alternativos que espero poder publicar para complementar este proyecto.

  • Audio Mod: Desviar la salida de sonido hacia arriba

LED Star,

I designed this star in Solidworks. The parts are printed on my 3D printer and the material is PETG. This material is very strong and nice to work with. In the beginning i had some problems with warping but later i used gluestick direct on the heated bed and had no warping at all. As connection rails i used aluminum LED channels with white covers. As controler i used a ESP32-WROOM module. At the moment i have only a few sequences installed but I'm working on a version where i can upload them via WiFi.
The whole star consists of 330 APA102 LED's which communicate via SPI. I have the SPI speed at 4 MHz and the refresh rate of the whole star is at 1 ms.

The making...

The APA102 LED's are in aluminum channels which are hold together by 3D printed connector parts. The material for those pars is PETG because it's very strong and easy to work with. The APA102 LED's are relative new on the market and i was looking for a project where i can use them for testing. This star seamed the perfect test project. At first I planned to use a CC3200 from TI as controller, but then i found the ESP32 modules and liked them more. Those modules contain WiFi and BLE on board and with the 2 core processor it's the most powerful module for it's size and price.

title: Modfied Clips For Glass Plate Mount
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Everybody knows about the cheap solution mounting a glass plate with these metall paper clips. However these clips are dangerous because your head can crash into if you don't take care.
I solved this problem easy by cutting off the thick end of the clip. It is a little bit more difficult to mount the clip after modification (i use a large screwdriver) but it works pretty well.
And now, i don't care any more about crashing, because the thickness of my clips is less than 0.3 mm and fits under my head. Update: Make absolutely sure that the clip does not press too firmly together. This can may in the long run break the glass. Use a screwdriver and pliers to wide the clip a little bit so that the glass is fitted enough not to slip - but not more.

comments.text: Good idea!  I'd fiddled with the PCB and aluminum bed frame to get it flat enough to use without glass, but had the clips in the middle of each side to stop it from bulging up from the aluminum.  It always bugged me the regular clips shrank the usable size of the bed probably 10mm in the X and Y dimension because of them sticking up and hitting the extruder.

This project contains the front panels for the Music From Outer Space "Sound Lab ULTIMATE" and "ULTIMATE EXPANDER"

The Sound Lab ULTIMATE is an analog electronic music synthesizer in the same spirit as a Moog synthesizer (e.g., the Minimoog), and the ULTIMATE EXPANDER turns the Ultimate into a full featured modular synthesizer. Ray Wilson, the designer of both of these electronic modules, describes the Sound Lab ULTIMATE as "simply put, one of the coolest things you will ever build with your own two hands". Head over to his web site at http://musicfromouterspace.com for the complete schematics, parts list, instructions, and links where you can purchase the PCBs.

I combined both ULTIMATE and ULTIMATE EXPANDER into the same box. The auxiliary panels combine both modules together (tp_left, tp_mid, and tp_right). I've also included separate auxiliary panels (ult_aux_panel and ult_ex_aux_panel) if you prefer to build these to modules in separate boxes (as Ray originally conceived).

I added an additional MIDI to CV feature in the case, so I could easily plug in my MIDI keyboard and play. The MIDI panel is labelled tp_left, and the electronics can be found at https://github.com/elkayem/midi2cv. You don't need to use this panel or electronics, but it is there if you want it.

The front panel includes raised text, and so must be printed with two colors. Most slicers include a "pause at height" plugin, which will move the hot end out of the way and allow you to switch filaments. The panels are 3mm thick, and the letters are 0.45mm thick. I printed with 0.15mm layer thickness, allowing the letters to be printed in three layers. Add the command to pause after you finish printing the 3mm layer, so you can change the filament color. (One tip: If you find that your printer is disabling the stepper motors after pausing, you may need to insert M84 S0 at the start of the G-Code. I did.)

The panel design is included in a SketchUp file. This file also includes dimensions for the case. I built the case out of 1" poplar panels from Home Depot (actually 0.75" thick), which are reasonably priced.

On my Folgertech 2020 i3, I mount my x-endstop on the left, and I'm in the process of moving to a slightly larger bed, and the original endstop finally gave up the ghost. So, I needed to make a new one. I don't currently use an add-on belt tensioner, and with the slightly wider bed (220x220 Anycubic Ultrabase with the mk3 heated bed) I wanted to maximize the workspace, which meant making as skinny of a mount as possible.

I like the arched design that Raloszekk had, since it not only uses both rots of the X-axis, but gets things out of the way of the belt (especially if I decide to add a tensioner in the future.)

I took Raloszekk's design, flipped it on the x-axis in Slic3r to get the mounting 'shelf' in the right direction and the wider clip on the bottom, exported it to an .stl file, and then used Tinkercad to chop 6mm out of the middle of it, so instead of being 22mm wide, it is now 16mm wide, the width of the actual endstop.

after printing it, I realized that the area where the "shelf" meets the "arch" could be moved a little bit to make the board sit more level in the narrower piece, but it fits and works for now, so I'm not going to worry about it until I need to.

description.text:
Wall mount for a bicycle pannier bag (like Ortlieb). The mounts allow you to store or load panniers off the bike. Mounting keeps the panniers off the ground, which reduces abrasion on the fabric and prolongs the bag's life. It also keeps your home/office looking more organized, because you don't have awkward bags lying around on the ground.

I was inspired by the "Wall Caddy, Bicycle Pannier Wall Mount", which I use two of for my smaller pannier bags. Unfortunately the Wall Caddy didn't work for my large Ortlieb panniers bags, with their clips set to their widest setting. I wanted to create a very inexpensive way to mount my pannier bag in different locations.

Requires 4 drywall screws.

The mounting holes are sized to work well with "drywall screws". This allows them to be mounted pretty much anywhere in a home or office. I didn't try it, but if you need to mount it to brick, I suggest trying to use two large "command strips" on the back, instead of screws.

Installation hint: clip one of the mounts into each of the two pannier bag mounts, and hold your bag on the wall. You should be able to mark a hole for the postion while holding the bag where you want it. Then remove the bag, level the mount, and put the second screw in. Mark and mount one of the them, then mark the other, and use a ruler to insure that they are level. Installation is really quick this way.

The diameter of the bar is 8mm, and you can change it by editing the OpenSCAD file on https://github.com/thrasher/pannier-mount

title: Robo3D X carriage bracket and fan duct

description.text:
EDIT: please see the newer revised edition here that is suitable for the Hexagon hotend. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:431160 During my 3D printing learning curve I found the requirement for ducted fan to achieve better prints and to successfully bridge. Since the Robo3D there wasn't any suitable fan ducts available on Thingiverse so I decided to try my hand at 3D CAD and design one, needless to say yet another steep learning curve.
This is my first design and I wanted to share it as I feel the bracket is a great solid fit for the Robo3D and I want it to help spawn some great fan ducts for the Robo. This duct fits with the E3D v5 nicely. To fit the standard hotend some tweaking is required (I had to file the duct bracket holes downwards a bit and some off the top of the duct brackets so the duct could mount to the X carriage bracket a bit higher, some users have heated the top of the duct and pushed the mounting point downwards). I hope you find this useful and that it assists in producing other/better fan ducts for the Robo3D.

Printed in PLA at 0.3 mm with 2 perimeters, 2 layers top/bottom, 25% infill. My fan duct print had some issues before it finished so it's about 5mm shorter than the design. Print the bracket on its side with support.
Print the duct on the fan attachment end with no support.
Drill the 4 duct fan mounting holes out with a 2.5mm drill bit.
Do some test fits if mounting with the stock hotend.
The X carriage bracket mounts on either side of the X carriage. Unbolt the stock fan and it's bracket then slide the bolt hole end of the new bracket on to the X carriage first then clip the bracket to the outside of the X carriage. The bracket will flex a little. Test fit the fan duct and make sure you have 2 or 3 mm clearance when the hot end is Z calibrated to the bed so you can slightly tilt it down towards the nozzle. Once fitted attach the fan with the stock bolts, you'll need to drill out the 4 fan mounting holes with a 2.5mm bit for the stock bolts to simply screw in. Then mount the duct to the bracket and check it's height and you're ready to do a test print.

I own a Freemotion 545 Ellptical, which has a pretty bad design flaw - there is a single track per foot, with a roller wheel that rides along it. On several occasions during exercise, one of my roller wheels fell off the track, almost causing me to fall off the machine and hurt myself. I decided to try to design a solution for this problem, and here it is. This replacement wheel is the same internal diameter (i.e. the part that sits on the track), but has a more aggressive curve, and the walls of the curve are larger, helping keep the wheel more securely in place.

I've printed this from PETG, for the strength and flexibility that material offers (with 80% infill, since it'll be bearing a lot of weight).

Use with 2 R10ZZ bearings.

All in all, about $15 worth of plastic and bearings (replacement units online go for ~$120), and solves the problem pretty well!

I didn't bother with the SEPARATION.stl file and instead hot glued the board in once it was tested. I only had single 18650 3.7V Battery holders and so hot glued 3 of those to the back panel.

I have modified all of the pieces for step 2 to allow for a bit of wiggle room, which makes the assembly much easier. Thanks to everyone who provided feedback!

This is an 8-Bit Link (as in The Legend of Zelda) hanging ornament made specifically for multi-extruder printers (though I have included a one-piece model for single-extruder machines). It's perfect for the rear-view mirror, Christmas tree, etc.

Please be aware that - though some post-printing assembly is required - the fully colourized version of this model was not designed to be printed in pieces on a single-extruder machine and assembled afterwards. Use link_onepiece.stl to get everything at once in a single colour.

The print in the cover photo was done on a quad extruder Prusa i3 MK2 MMU as follows:

Step 1:

  • link_step1_white.stl white PLA (extruder 1)
  • link_step1_red.stl red PLA (extruder 2)

Step 2:

  • link_step2_brown.stl brown PLA (extruder 1)
  • link_step2_flesh.stl pale flesh PLA (extruder 2)
  • link_step2_green.stl green PLA (extruder 3)

Assembly:
Because I used more colours than I have extruders, some post-printing assembly is required. I have allowed for some wiggle room between the various parts, so things should fit together fairly easily with little-to-no sanding/clean-up. You basically just have to glue the Link model onto the white backplate and add a string/wire for hanging.

For those of you who have fewer extruders (or who like painting a lot more than I do), I have included link_onepiece.stl, which can be used to print everything at once in a single colour/material, no post-printing assembly required.

When printed at 100% size, the ornament measures approximately 42mm x 48mm.

Happy printing!

title: Audio Technica ES Series Over Ear Earpad Adapter (ES10, ES7, ES9, ES700, ES500 etc)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The Audio Technica ES series of headphones are amazing but come at the cost of comfort. Unfortunately sore ears are inevitable after a few hours. This adapter allows over ear style earpads to be used.

This gives much better comfort for extended listening sessions, better noise isolation in noisy environments and after some tweaking sound better than the stock pads.

It is 100% tested and confirmed compatible with the ES10's but should also work with other headphones in the ES series.

It is designed around AH-MSR7 earpads but should also work with Sennheiser momentum over ear pads and Audio Technica M40/M50 Series pads. The pads I used are non authentic clones which are available for cheap on eBay and aliexpress etc. They may sound different than genuine MSR7 pads.

The sound signature is changed fairly drastically. Using MSR7 Pads without any alterations on the ES10 causes a larger soundstage, sharper treble and very slightly recessed mids.

The ideal combination is a sheet of 3ply toilet paper between the driver and the earpad. This tames the treble peak, brings back the midrange, while the bass impact and soundstage is retained. It sounds better than the stock ES10 in my opinion and also possibly better than the ES10 with ESW11 sheepskin earpads. In conjunction with the increased comfort it is a very worthwhile mod.

Thinner pads will probably alter the sound signature the least as they position the head close to the original earpads. Thicker and angled pads will create a bigger soundstage, but can cause changes to treble. This can be managed surprisingly well with toilet paper.

title: Dishwasher Cutlery Basket Base for Hotpoint

description.text:
I am now on my 3rd Dishwasher Cutlery Basket for my dishwasher and I simply refuse the buy a 4th even though they are now only £16. Since it is always the bases that break I thought I would 3d print some reinforcement plates.

There are some already on Thingiverse but there were two issues, 1) finding the correct size, 2) the basic design can be difficult to print as small unsupported circles sit independently on the bed until about half way through the print when they start to join each other. These tend to want to lift from the bed.

With this design there is a thin crisscross design that holds these in place without using printing supports.

Finished size is 68 x 52 x 7mm and drop down into the original sections of the basket.You will need to print 4 of them, one for each section.

Tested in ABS on the hottest wash (65c intensive) there are no issues.

comments.text: Perhaps you could pick up some conductive paint? You'd need to cover the bottom and top of the stick, plus a little line connecting the two. You could also try a little piece of copper tape cut into a circle, but you'd still need to connect it to a conductor of some kind on the top that you could touch I think. If you go this route make sure there are not wrinkles or sharp corners that could scratch the pad. Another thought is to buy a pair of those knit stretch gloves that allow you to operate your phone (there are soft conductive strands in the fabric). Cut off a fingertip and glue it to the stick component.  Finally, you could apply a little copper or silver(aluminum) leaf -- you can pick it up at Michael's. I've had good luck making 3D prints look metallic that way, and they're conductive. You'd need to smooth the part first before applying the leaf. Go google fishing for specific directions. It's not particularly difficult if you can put up with imperfections in the finish.
